[[Image:Burg-Fuersteneck front www.burg-fuersteneck.de.jpg|thumb|Fürsteneck Castle from the south]] [[File:Burghof Burg Fürsteneck.jpg|thumb|Inner ward of the castle]] [[Image:Www.burg-fuersteneck.de aerial view.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of the castle]] [[Image:Karte Fulda in Deutschland.png|thumb|Location of Fürsteneck Castle in Germany]]
'''Fürsteneck Castle''' ({{lang-de|Burg Fürsteneck}}) is a [[castle]], situated in central [[Germany]] between [[Fulda]] and [[Bad Hersfeld]]. It belongs to the commune of [[Eiterfeld]]. The castle is at an elevation of 406 metres on a small [[plateau]].
==History== Fürsteneck Castle belonged to the [[monastery]] of Fulda. The first written mention of it dates to 1309, but it might have been built one or two hundred years before. After [[secularization]] in 1802, it became the property of the German state of [[Hesse]].
==Akademie Burg Fürsteneck== Since 1952 the castle has been used as an [[academy]] for [[vocational education|vocational]] and cultural [[continuing education]]. It was rebuilt by the architect [[Otto Bartning]]. Each year about 4,000 participants take part in one of nearly 200 courses, with 15,000 overnight stays.
